+## Run Doctor
+
+`flowai-workflow runs doctor --workflow <dir> --run <run-id>` (FR-E83)
+diagnoses a run's durability artifacts — the append-only `journal.jsonl`, the
+run directory, and the `runs/.lock` — and reports **every** problem grouped by
+severity (ERROR / WARNING / OK). It only inspects: replay invariants are
+checked through the existing journal replayer, never a second one. Exit code
+is `0` when no ERRORs are found, `1` otherwise.
+
+```
+flowai-workflow runs doctor --workflow <dir> --run <run-id> [--repair] [--json]
+
+  --repair   Apply ONLY safe mechanical fixes, each reported: drop a torn
+             final journal line (backs up to journal.jsonl.bak, then atomically
+             rewrites without the torn line) and remove a stale lock. Refuses
+             (nothing modified) when the run is active or the journal has any
+             error beyond the torn final line.
+  --json     Emit a machine-readable findings list:
+             { run_id, run_dir, ok, findings:[{ severity, code, message,
+             evidence }], repair? }.
+```
+
+Checks: journal integrity (parse errors, unknown event kinds, non-monotonic
+`seq`, duplicate `event_id`), replay invariants (events after a terminal run
+event, lifecycle for undeclared nodes, `attempt_completed` without a start,
+cost-sum divergence), and a filesystem cross-check (orphan vs missing node
+directories, stale lock).
+
 ## Embedded MCP Server
 
 `flowai-workflow mcp <workflow>` starts an embedded Model Context Protocol
