+# `runs doctor` — journal health checker with mechanical repair
+
+## Goal
+
+Give operators a single command to diagnose a run's durability artifacts
+(`journal.jsonl`, the run directory, the workflow lock) and apply *only* safe,
+mechanical repairs. Crashes, manual tampering, and engine bugs can degrade a
+journal; today the only recovery signal is a hard replay throw with no triage
+and no guided fix. `runs doctor` turns that opaque failure into a graded,
+machine-readable report plus a narrow, reversible repair path.
+
+## Overview
+
+### Context
+
+A run's only durable record is its append-only
+`<workflow>/runs/<run-id>/journal.jsonl`, replayed by the EXISTING replayer in
+`src/state/run-journal.ts` (`replayRunJournal`) to reconstruct `RunState`
+(FR-E69). The replayer is intentionally strict: it throws on the first
+malformed non-tail line, on a missing `run_started`, and on a mixed-run
+journal. That is correct for recovery but useless for triage — an operator
+needs EVERY problem listed, grouped by severity, and a safe way to drop the
+one artifact the writer already tolerates (a torn final line from a crash mid
+`Deno.writeTextFile`).
+
+Sibling durability helpers already exist and MUST be reused (no duplication):
+- `src/state/state.ts` — `getRunDir(runId, workflowDir)`.
+- `src/state/run-journal.ts` — `getJournalPath(runDir)`, `replayRunJournal`
+  (the single source of replay truth; `RunJournalReplayResult` exposes
+  deduped `events` + reconstructed `state`).
+- `src/state/lock.ts` — `defaultLockPath(workflowDir)`, `readLockInfo`,
+  `LockInfo`, `releaseLock`, and the process-liveness primitive
+  (`isProcessAlive`, currently private — to be exported for reuse).
+
+The CLI (`src/cli.ts`) dispatches subcommands (`run`/`answer`/`init`/`mcp`)
+with hand-rolled positional/flag loops (`parseArgs`, `parseAnswerArgs`); the
+project pattern keeps a thin CLI over a fat, unit-testable core
+(`src/mcp/commands.ts`, `src/state/*`).
+
+### Current State
+
+- No `runs` subcommand exists. CLI subcommands are routed in the
+  `if (import.meta.main)` block of `src/cli.ts`; `printUsage()` renders help.
+- `replayRunJournal` returns `{ state, events, ignored_duplicate_event_ids,
+  ignored_partial_tail }`; the replayer recomputes `state.total_cost_usd` as
+  the sum of per-node snapshot costs on every node-lifecycle event.
+- Valid journal `kind` values are the 18 members of `RunJournalEventKind`
+  (`src/types.ts`). Node-lifecycle events carry both a `node` snapshot and a
+  flat metadata mirror (`cost_usd`, …) sourced from the same node state.
+- The per-workflow lock lives at `<workflowDir>/runs/.lock` (`LockInfo` =
+  `{pid, hostname, run_id, started_at}`); stale = recorded PID not alive.
+- `documents/requirements-engine/01-execution-model.md` is the
+  durability/recovery SRS area (FR-E5/E9/E14/E25). FR-E83 is the next free id
+  (current max FR-E82).
+
+### Constraints
+
+- No new dependencies. Follow the existing arg-parsing style in `src/cli.ts`.
+- The existing replayer is the SOLE replay truth — doctor only orchestrates
+  and inspects its result. Writing a second replayer is forbidden. (The
+  journal-integrity phase is lexical line-scanning, NOT replay — it exists
+  precisely because the replayer aborts on the first bad line and cannot
+  enumerate every problem.)
+- Reuse `src/state/` helpers for run/node/lock paths and lock parsing; do not
+  duplicate path construction or lock-file knowledge.
+- Read-only by default; `--repair` performs ONLY: drop a torn final line
+  (backup `journal.jsonl.bak` + atomic tmp-write+rename) and remove a stale
+  lock. Refuse (clear error, NOTHING modified) when the run is active (live
+  lock) or the journal has any error beyond the torn final line.
+- No journal compaction/rewriting beyond the torn final line; no multi-run
+  batch mode (one `--run`); no interactive prompts (flags only).
+- `deno task check` stays green; register FR-E83 in the SRS per project
+  conventions (canonical FR field set; `documents/AGENTS.md`).
