+## Solution
+
+### Selected variant — B: dedicated `src/state/doctor.ts` + thin CLI wiring
+
+**Variant analysis (autonomous selection — no human in benchmark).**
+
+- **A — Quick fix: inline in `cli.ts`.** Pros: fewest files; literal reading
+  of "follow cli.ts arg style". Cons: bloats the CLI entry with ~300 lines of
+  diagnostics; `cli.ts` is `Deno.exit`/`import.meta.main`-driven and not
+  unit-testable, but the Constraints DEMAND a large unit-test matrix on
+  fabricated run dirs. Risk: untestable, breaks the project's thin-CLI/fat-core
+  separation. Best for: throwaway.
+- **B — Architecturally-correct: `src/state/doctor.ts` (pure, returns a
+  structured `DoctorReport`) + thin `cli.ts` wiring.** Pros: mirrors the
+  established thin-interface/fat-core convention (`commands.ts`, `state.ts`);
+  fully unit-testable without spawning the CLI; cohesive next to
+  `run-journal.ts`/`lock.ts`/`state.ts`; reuses helpers per constraint. Cons:
+  one new module + a one-line `isProcessAlive` export on `lock.ts`. Risk:
+  minimal. Best for: a durable feature with a test matrix — this task.
+- **C — Best long-term: put doctor in the FR-E75 command layer
+  (`src/mcp/commands.ts`) for future MCP reuse.** Pros: a future MCP `doctor`
+  tool would need zero refactor. Cons: YAGNI — the task is explicitly
+  flags-only/one-run with no MCP ask; `commands.ts` is run-control *mutations*
+  (answer/resume), not read-only diagnostics; couples a heavy diagnostic to the
+  Engine import graph. Risk: over-engineering beyond scope. Best for: only if
+  an MCP doctor were a near-term requirement (it is not).
+
+**Trade-offs.** A minimizes files but sacrifices the testability the
+Constraints require. C maximizes speculative reuse but over-builds past the
+task's stated scope. **B** hits testability + separation + reuse at minimal
+cost and matches existing project structure. **Selected: B.**
